  "text": "More broadly, when symbolic numbers (e.g., \"8\") were presented to both adults and children, regardless of modality, magnitude representation was automatically activated, even in cases where a task did not require a judgment of magnitude [CITATION_1] . Internal magnitude representation is ordinal, with numbers cognitively organized so that smaller numbers are associated with the left side and larger numbers are associated with the right side in external space [CITATION_2] . Therefore, subjects respond more quickly to larger numbers with their right hands and smaller numbers with their left hands. In addition, subjects respond more quickly to comparisons when numbers are farther apart from one another than when they are closer together (distance effect), indicating that people have stronger connections between numbers that are closer on a number line [CITATION_3] . Together, this research has provided evidence for internal magnitude representation as a \"mental number line.\"",
